{{Infobox OS | name = | logo = | screenshot = | caption = | developer = | family = [[Unix-like]], [[Linux]] | working_state = | source_model = [[Open source]] | released = | latest_release_version = | latest_release_date = | latest_preview_version = | latest_preview_date = | frequently_updated = | marketing_target = | language = | prog_language = | updatemodel = [[Advanced Packaging Tool|APT]] | package_manager = [[dpkg]] (Debian Packager) | supported_platforms = | kernel_type = [[Monolithic kernel|Monolithic]] ([[Linux kernel|Linux]]) | userland = | ui = | license = mainly [[open source]] | preceded_by = | succeeded_by = | website = http://vinuxproject.org }} '''Vinux''' is a [[Linux distribution]] which has been specially designed for [[blindness|blind]] and [[visual impairment|partially sighted]] users. Specifically it is a remastered version of the popular [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] distribution and provides users with two screen-readers, two full-screen magnifiers, global font-size and colour changing facilities. The system also supports USB [[Refreshable Braille display|Braille displays]]. Vinux was originally developed in 2008 by Tony Sales, a lecturer at the [[Royal National College for the Blind]] in [[Hereford]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.excellencegateway.org.uk/page.aspx?o=256746|title= Royal National College for the Blind: Vinux for the visually impaired|work= Excellence Gateway|publisher= Learning and Skills Improvement Service|date= 22 October 2009|accessdate= 11 August 2010}}</ref> It was first listed on [[DistroWatch]] on 1 June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://distrowatch.com/table.php?distribution=vinux|title= DistroWatch Vinux Page|date= 1 June 2010|accessdate= 21 December 2010 2010}}</ref>
==Features== Vinux allows blind and visually impaired computer users to install a version of Ubuntu independently. It includes [[Orca (assistive technology)|Orca]] (a [[screen reader]] and magnifier), [[Speakup]] (a [[Command-line interface|console]] screen reader), [[Compiz]] (a magnifier based on 3d technology), and support for Braille displays. Braille displays operate automatically when connected and support grade 1 and 2 [[Braille]]. Vinux can run from a [[live cd]] without making any changes to a current operating system. It can be installed to a usb or hard drive alongside a current operating system or as a complete replacement.
